<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does slushie machine repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our diagnostic fee is $120, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most slushie machine repairs run between $150 and $500. Auger seal, thermostat, drive motor, or dispense valve is toward the lower end. Compressor or refrigerant work runs significantly higher. We provide a full written estimate before any work begins. For machines where the repair cost approaches replacement cost, we'll tell you honestly."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My slushie machine is producing product that's too frozen or not frozen enough — what causes that?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Both issues usually trace back to the thermostat or temperature control system. Too frozen: the thermostat is not reading the product temperature accurately and allowing the refrigeration cycle to run too long. Not frozen enough: the refrigeration cycle is cutting off too early, or the compressor is underperforming due to dirty condenser coils or low refrigerant. Mix viscosity (brix/sugar content) also affects freeze point significantly — if you've changed your mix recently, that may be the cause before any component failure."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need to clean my slushie machine regularly?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes — this is a LADPH health code requirement, not just a maintenance recommendation. Commercial slushie machines using dairy-based, juice-based, or sugar syrup mixes must be cleaned and sanitized on a schedule required by California food service code. The warm mixing zone between the product and the ambient air is an ideal environment for bacterial and mold growth. Pink slime, black mold, or discoloration inside the bowl or dispensing tube means the machine is out of compliance and should be pulled from service immediately."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My slushie machine won't dispense or has very slow flow — what's causing it?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Slow or no dispensing on a slushie machine is almost always a product consistency issue or a mechanical dispensing valve problem. If the product is too thick (over-frozen), it creates back pressure in the dispensing tube. If the product is the right consistency but won't flow, the dispensing valve or spigot mechanism has failed. On granita-style machines, a jammed or worn auger can prevent product from reaching the dispense point."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Bunn, Elmeco, Carpigiani, and Frosty Factory slushie machines?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Bunn, Elmeco, Carpigiani, Frosty Factory, and Taylor are the brands we service most in LA. We source parts through commercial food service equipment distributors. For older machines or unusual configurations, we'll confirm parts availability before scheduling. All refrigerant work is performed by EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410) technicians."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should a commercial slushie machine be serviced in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Full disassembly cleaning and sanitization: every 2 weeks for dairy-based mix machines, monthly for juice and syrup-based machines — per California food service code guidance. Preventive mechanical service (condenser cleaning, auger inspection, seal check, refrigerant verification): every 6 months. In LA's warm ambient temperatures, condenser coils on slushie machines accumulate dust faster than in cooler climates, affecting cooling efficiency."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

